WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.166 --> 00:00:02.300
So we're going to San Francisco today.

00:00:02.366 --> 00:00:04.166
That's right. I was gonna say—

00:00:04.166 --> 00:00:05.800
let me know when you're in autonomous mode.

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:08.966
Then I could be less concerned about my safety.

00:00:09.233 --> 00:00:11.766
We have the only stack in the world that has an

00:00:11.766 --> 00:00:13.500
end-to-end— that's right—

00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:15.033
AV stack, that's right,

00:00:15.033 --> 00:00:18.966
as well as a traceable, human-engineered one.

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:22.166
That's right, that's right.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Which is very critical because,

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:26.000
you know, for an end-to-end model,

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:27.700
it's very difficult to verify

00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:29.633
that basically it's always safe, right?

00:00:29.633 --> 00:00:30.100
That's right.

00:00:30.100 --> 00:00:33.466
And the classical stack is developed based on all the

00:00:33.666 --> 00:00:35.100
safety protocols and the process.

00:00:35.100 --> 00:00:38.466
We know how to ensure safety in software.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:42.266
Yeah, the thing that's a miracle about Autopilot

00:00:42.266 --> 00:00:44.200
is that it does amazing things.

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:45.866
Yeah, and it drives like a human.

00:00:45.966 --> 00:00:46.966
That's right. Um—

00:00:46.966 --> 00:00:48.500
Because it's—

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:49.866
because it's end-to-end,

00:00:49.866 --> 00:00:52.600
whenever there are things that need to be improved,

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:54.500
you know that

00:00:54.500 --> 00:00:57.766
you can backpropagate that through the whole model,

00:00:57.766 --> 00:00:59.400
and you'll improve it for sure.

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:00.366
Yeah, I think the—

00:01:00.366 --> 00:01:01.366
the challenge, of course,

00:01:01.366 --> 00:01:03.166
is our AV model, as—

00:01:03.633 --> 00:01:05.533
as incredibly smart as it is,

00:01:05.766 --> 00:01:08.700
and it can reason about the circumstances,

00:01:08.766 --> 00:01:10.900
we don't know what it can't do.

00:01:10.900 --> 00:01:11.866
That's right, yeah.

00:01:11.866 --> 00:01:13.833
And so that's—

00:01:13.833 --> 00:01:15.233
that's the challenge, and that's the reason

00:01:15.233 --> 00:01:17.600
why our classical stack is so incredibly important.

00:01:17.600 --> 00:01:18.400
That's right.

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:20.666
The thing that's really great about our AV model

00:01:20.666 --> 00:01:23.666
and our stack is that I don't ever feel

00:01:23.666 --> 00:01:26.166
that our AV model would ever be allowed to do

00:01:26.166 --> 00:01:27.366
something

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:29.966
that is out of distribution.

00:01:30.033 --> 00:01:31.233
And the reason for that

00:01:31.233 --> 00:01:33.000
is because our classical stack gets involved

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:35.333
and prevents it from happening, right?

00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:41.700
One thing great about our AV model

00:01:41.700 --> 00:01:44.266
is the development speed is just amazing.

00:01:44.266 --> 00:01:46.233
You know, we have iterated the—

00:01:46.233 --> 00:01:49.933
right now the version is, I think, twenty-three hundred.

00:01:50.566 --> 00:01:53.433
We label based on the number of iterations we have,

00:01:53.433 --> 00:01:55.266
essentially, and roughly speaking,

00:01:55.266 --> 00:01:56.700
we have, you know—

00:01:56.700 --> 00:01:58.400
this is roughly over a year, right?

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:02.900
So we have, on average, less than seven models being

00:02:02.900 --> 00:02:05.466
iterated every day. Obviously not every—

00:02:05.466 --> 00:02:07.500
every single one of them makes it to the car.

00:02:07.866 --> 00:02:10.466
But because this process is,

00:02:10.466 --> 00:02:13.866
you know, just the imaging and trajectory output,

00:02:13.966 --> 00:02:16.700
there's manual steps in between,

00:02:16.700 --> 00:02:17.666
in the development process,

00:02:17.666 --> 00:02:18.466
they're just minimal.

00:02:18.466 --> 00:02:20.533
That's why we can iterate super fast.

00:02:20.900 --> 00:02:23.000
Well—
The thing that's really great about end-to-end models

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:26.000
is that whenever you're improving the model—

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:27.000
uh-huh, um—

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.866
because it's one giant model that's end-to-end—

00:02:29.866 --> 00:02:30.933
that's right—

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:34.466
you're not gonna fix one thing and break something else.

00:02:34.466 --> 00:02:35.800
The classical models—

00:02:35.800 --> 00:02:37.366
because there's so many different modules,

00:02:37.366 --> 00:02:38.666
you fix this one thing,

00:02:38.666 --> 00:02:40.666
the logic sometimes contradicts with each other.

00:02:40.666 --> 00:02:41.866
That's right, yeah.

00:02:42.033 --> 00:02:44.600
And so it's so brittle, and you fix one thing,

00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:46.500
you're chasing bugs all around the table,

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:48.066
and it's really hard, you know.

00:02:48.066 --> 00:02:51.433
Most control systems which are built the classical way

00:02:51.433 --> 00:02:52.866
have the same problem.

00:02:52.866 --> 00:02:56.500
And it has so many steps.

00:02:56.633 --> 00:02:57.600
For example, right,

00:02:57.600 --> 00:02:59.500
today we're actually gonna see a speed bump.

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:01.200
You know, based on our model,

00:03:01.500 --> 00:03:02.566
if you think about it,

00:03:02.566 --> 00:03:05.533
how do you detect a speed bump and react to it properly?

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:06.866
You have to break it into many,

00:03:06.866 --> 00:03:09.366
many steps, from perception and—

00:03:09.366 --> 00:03:11.633
you know, it has to be added in the world model,

00:03:11.633 --> 00:03:12.966
in the context fusion,

00:03:13.366 --> 00:03:15.666
and then basically you have to decide

00:03:15.766 --> 00:03:18.866
how early you have to slow down, by how much,

00:03:18.900 --> 00:03:19.766
you know, and—

00:03:19.766 --> 00:03:22.033
maybe even based on different speed bumps,

00:03:22.033 --> 00:03:23.333
we have to do things differently.

00:03:23.433 --> 00:03:25.800
But with the end-to-end model, it just—

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:27.566
basically just happen, actually.

00:03:27.566 --> 00:03:30.800
We didn't even plan for it. It just happened.

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:31.366
Yeah, right.

00:03:31.366 --> 00:03:33.500
So it's pretty amazing.

00:03:33.566 --> 00:03:35.966
There's so many people building end-to-end models, right?

00:03:35.966 --> 00:03:39.233
But I really think that it's the fusion of the two—

00:03:39.233 --> 00:03:40.500
yes, that's revolutionary—

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:41.666
that gives you

00:03:41.666 --> 00:03:43.066
the superhuman—

00:03:43.066 --> 00:03:45.200
amazing driving capability and the safety.

00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:47.833
And back to the model, actually, you know,

00:03:47.833 --> 00:03:48.866
it does—

00:03:48.866 --> 00:03:51.300
because it's so big, right?

00:03:51.300 --> 00:03:53.100
Actually, we do see sometimes,

00:03:53.100 --> 00:03:55.300
you know, when you try to address something,

00:03:55.466 --> 00:03:57.500
it has some, you know—

00:03:57.500 --> 00:04:00.033
something else might get regressed, right?

00:04:00.033 --> 00:04:04.966
So being able to establish a basically full-blown,

00:04:04.966 --> 00:04:07.033
very comprehensive,

00:04:07.033 --> 00:04:09.100
basically a closed-loop evaluation,

00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:11.200
what we call CLE, is super critical.

00:04:11.366 --> 00:04:13.400
This is how we gate our model,

00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:16.766
to make sure sort of the bad behaviors, yeah,

00:04:16.800 --> 00:04:19.500
get filtered out. The thing that I still love, though,

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:22.200
and I think this proves to be true—

00:04:22.433 --> 00:04:25.266
that even when you have a regression on our AV model,

00:04:26.266 --> 00:04:28.666
your classical stack would always guardrail it.

00:04:28.666 --> 00:04:30.066
That's right, actually.

00:04:30.066 --> 00:04:31.566
That's why, basically,

00:04:31.666 --> 00:04:34.466
our development speed has been so good,

00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:37.566
because you always have a backup, essentially.

00:04:37.566 --> 00:04:38.366
That's right, you know—

00:04:38.366 --> 00:04:40.166
even if you have minor hiccups—

00:04:40.166 --> 00:04:40.766
that's right, okay—

00:04:40.766 --> 00:04:42.800
we will keep retraining, and—

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:43.233
that's right, you know—

00:04:43.233 --> 00:04:44.733
just keep getting better.

00:04:44.766 --> 00:04:46.266
You never have a loss of safety.

00:04:46.266 --> 00:04:47.633
You have a loss of capability,

00:04:47.633 --> 00:04:49.466
but not a loss of safety, yeah.

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:53.966
This is gonna be so critical for a robotaxi.

00:04:55.266 --> 00:04:57.166
When that happens, you know what I'm saying.

00:04:57.166 --> 00:04:57.966
That's right.

00:04:58.866 --> 00:05:00.700
That is the advantage we have,

00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:03.333
as well as we move into L3 and L4.

00:05:03.400 --> 00:05:05.033
Because we have redundant stack,

00:05:05.033 --> 00:05:07.400
even L2++—to scale it, basically—

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:08.566
for L3 and L4, it's—

00:05:08.566 --> 00:05:10.600
it's just so natural. That's right.

00:05:11.666 --> 00:05:12.933
Yeah, that's critical.

00:05:13.633 --> 00:05:14.966
And then, and then, um—

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:17.400
then there'll be the—

00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:18.333
teleoperations.

00:05:19.433 --> 00:05:20.833
Right, as a backup system.

00:05:20.833 --> 00:05:22.633
And then, you know, every—

00:05:22.633 --> 00:05:24.033
every robotaxi—

00:05:24.033 --> 00:05:26.266
every robotaxi service should have,

00:05:26.866 --> 00:05:30.066
you know, an air traffic control center.

00:05:30.766 --> 00:05:32.900
And the thing that's really great with our technology

00:05:32.900 --> 00:05:33.766
is that—

00:05:34.466 --> 00:05:35.466
for whatever reason,

00:05:35.466 --> 00:05:37.733
if the robotaxi were to get stuck—

00:05:37.766 --> 00:05:40.266
uh-huh—
all you have to do is give it a couple of waypoints.

00:05:41.633 --> 00:05:43.433
The human-injected waypoint.

00:05:43.433 --> 00:05:45.100
That's right, and it should be able to navigate itself

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:46.900
right out of it, right?

00:05:47.233 --> 00:05:49.133
And because it has a—

00:05:49.300 --> 00:05:52.566
has a safety stack, a backup stack—

00:05:52.700 --> 00:05:55.500
no safety would ever be jeopardized.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:58.100
That's right. And the other thing our AV model does really,

00:05:58.100 --> 00:06:00.700
really well is lane-changing capability.

00:06:02.200 --> 00:06:04.300
Because classically, when we do a lane change,

00:06:04.300 --> 00:06:05.566
we have to select the gap,

00:06:05.566 --> 00:06:07.000
we have to do a lot of, basically,

00:06:07.033 --> 00:06:09.233
rules and heuristics, essentially, right?

00:06:09.233 --> 00:06:12.233
to make sure it's safe. So sometimes it's a bit timid,

00:06:12.233 --> 00:06:13.566
essentially, when you have,

00:06:13.700 --> 00:06:15.000
you know, cars in the front,

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:16.166
you have cars in the back,

00:06:16.166 --> 00:06:18.066
basically there's so many rules.

00:06:18.066 --> 00:06:19.700
That's right, yeah, yeah.

00:06:20.300 --> 00:06:22.833
And the AV model, basically, in the city,

00:06:22.833 --> 00:06:25.500
it's just doing an amazing job in the lane change.

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:27.433
It's also very human-like, essentially,

00:06:27.433 --> 00:06:30.700
and never gives you the feeling of rigidity.

00:06:31.033 --> 00:06:31.700
Well, it—

00:06:31.700 --> 00:06:32.766
it imitates the human

00:06:32.766 --> 00:06:34.433
from all the drives that it's been on.

00:06:34.433 --> 00:06:36.233
Yeah, and then it generalizes from that.

00:06:36.233 --> 00:06:37.666
That's right, yeah.

00:06:38.366 --> 00:06:40.533
You know, the basic concept of deep learning

00:06:41.066 --> 00:06:44.966
is essentially to memorize and generalize.

00:06:46.566 --> 00:06:48.600
Works just fine for a self-driving car.

00:06:49.233 --> 00:06:52.833
AI is the single most important technology

00:06:52.833 --> 00:06:56.166
that made self-driving possible, essentially.

00:06:56.166 --> 00:06:57.666
But, um—

00:06:58.266 --> 00:06:59.400
you know, I have been working on this,

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:00.200
obviously, as you know,

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:02.200
for a long time, but the last two—

00:07:02.200 --> 00:07:03.500
three years, my God—

00:07:03.500 --> 00:07:04.500
you know, yeah—

00:07:04.500 --> 00:07:05.300
just—

00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:07.833
it's iterating so fast.

00:07:07.833 --> 00:07:08.633
Yeah.

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:11.466
If you think about particularly the—

00:07:11.466 --> 00:07:12.266
the, uh—

00:07:12.866 --> 00:07:14.500
using an end-to-end model—

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:15.800
that's right, yeah—

00:07:15.800 --> 00:07:17.300
was a big deal, yeah.

00:07:17.300 --> 00:07:18.600
Yeah, basically—

00:07:21.700 --> 00:07:23.566
to some extent, you can think that the—

00:07:23.566 --> 00:07:26.366
the whole industry iterated on the first architecture,

00:07:26.366 --> 00:07:27.966
which is, you know, um—

00:07:27.966 --> 00:07:30.233
ML-based perception only, right?

00:07:30.233 --> 00:07:31.466
For ten years, yeah.

00:07:31.466 --> 00:07:33.466
And we made lots of progress.

00:07:33.466 --> 00:07:34.433
You know, you know—

00:07:34.433 --> 00:07:36.966
robotaxi can be done that way.

00:07:36.966 --> 00:07:38.400
Yeah, um—

00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:40.700
But, you know, over the last three years,

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:42.000
we're iterating on, you know—

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:43.966
we first brought in a world model,

00:07:43.966 --> 00:07:45.500
now we're adding reasoning to it.

00:07:45.500 --> 00:07:47.833
It's really two generations in three years.

00:07:47.833 --> 00:07:50.100
The two fundamental technologies

00:07:50.100 --> 00:07:51.900
that we're building on top of.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:52.600
You know, so—

00:07:52.600 --> 00:07:53.200
so of course,

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:56.366
this end-to-end model architecture is revolutionary.

00:07:56.366 --> 00:07:58.866
But what differentiates us—

00:07:58.866 --> 00:08:00.300
uh-huh, um—

00:08:00.466 --> 00:08:03.266
and what's gonna make it incredibly fast

00:08:03.266 --> 00:08:05.366
for us to deploy to get to Level 3,

00:08:05.366 --> 00:08:06.966
Level 4, and robotaxis—

00:08:07.266 --> 00:08:10.266
is the fact that we have a classical stack

00:08:10.266 --> 00:08:13.133
as a guardrail, as a safety system.

00:08:13.200 --> 00:08:15.866
And because we have a reasoning system—

00:08:15.866 --> 00:08:16.666
uh-huh—

00:08:17.400 --> 00:08:20.666
so the long tail of experiences that are

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:24.866
probably not in our dataset,

00:08:25.066 --> 00:08:27.766
can still be decomposed into routine,

00:08:27.766 --> 00:08:30.766
type of experiences that are in our dataset.

00:08:30.766 --> 00:08:33.700
Yeah, and the car will be able to reason its way through,

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:36.233
you know, how to navigate and how to operate.

00:08:36.233 --> 00:08:39.300
And so I really think that between these two ideas,

00:08:39.700 --> 00:08:42.366
no matter what the reasoning system decides to do or

00:08:42.366 --> 00:08:43.700
or achieve,

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:46.300
you always have a safety guardrail behind it.

00:08:46.866 --> 00:08:49.066
And so this iteration system that we have

00:08:49.066 --> 00:08:50.966
is going to move incredibly fast.

00:08:50.966 --> 00:08:51.600
The reasoning—

00:08:51.600 --> 00:08:54.600
and guardrailing—is going to be just revolutionary.

00:08:54.600 --> 00:08:56.433
That's right. All of our—

00:08:56.433 --> 00:08:57.833
all of our—

00:08:57.833 --> 00:08:59.666
L2++ work—

00:08:59.766 --> 00:09:01.600
that entire flywheel—

00:09:01.633 --> 00:09:02.700
you know—

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:04.466
collecting data on the road and—

00:09:04.466 --> 00:09:05.066
that's right, you know—

00:09:05.066 --> 00:09:07.100
processing the data—

00:09:07.700 --> 00:09:09.066
now we enhance that by

00:09:09.066 --> 00:09:10.433
using Neurad and—

00:09:10.433 --> 00:09:11.100
and, and—

00:09:11.100 --> 00:09:12.466
and then Cosmos.

00:09:13.166 --> 00:09:14.500
Yeah, good job.

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:16.000
Good job.

00:09:18.266 --> 00:09:20.333
Who knows what a human driver would have done.

00:09:24.666 --> 00:09:25.900
That's pretty good.

00:09:27.033 --> 00:09:29.300
Yeah, that entire flywheel is essential.

00:09:29.300 --> 00:09:30.700
Yup, yup.

00:09:32.700 --> 00:09:34.700
As I said, right, on the model side,

00:09:34.700 --> 00:09:35.566
you know—

00:09:35.566 --> 00:09:37.600
closed-loop evaluation is so important.

00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:39.166
We are running essentially—

00:09:39.166 --> 00:09:39.833
you know, as you know—

00:09:39.833 --> 00:09:42.333
two million tests every day.

00:09:42.366 --> 00:09:44.466
And they are all pixel-based, basically—

00:09:45.666 --> 00:09:47.000
reconstruction of the world.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:50.166
It's just amazing, basically, how the technology evolves.

00:09:50.700 --> 00:09:51.300
The neural reconstruction we have—

00:09:51.300 --> 00:09:52.600
it's so great, yes.

00:09:52.600 --> 00:09:54.200
That's right. It's so critical.

00:09:54.300 --> 00:09:56.900
And then Cosmos can be introduced as well,

00:09:56.900 --> 00:09:58.633
which we are working on, basically,

00:09:58.633 --> 00:10:00.000
to add—

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.566
Cosmos can cover the really rare corner cases,

00:10:02.566 --> 00:10:05.900
and also it can be used to amplify the neural reconstruction.

00:10:05.900 --> 00:10:07.200
Neural reconstruction is just reconstruction,

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:08.866
but if you put Cosmos on it,

00:10:08.866 --> 00:10:09.666
it can—

00:10:10.033 --> 00:10:10.966
you know, change the—

00:10:10.966 --> 00:10:11.800
you know, background,

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:12.966
change the weather, yeah.

00:10:12.966 --> 00:10:14.433
You could augment it, that's right.

00:10:14.433 --> 00:10:16.366
Yeah, that's right, exactly, yeah.

00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:18.166
The combination of these technologies

00:10:18.166 --> 00:10:20.200
has really been revolutionary, yeah.

00:10:22.033 --> 00:10:24.266
There's probably an accident here somewhere.

00:10:24.666 --> 00:10:27.333
Well, they really ought to get one of our cars.

00:10:31.766 --> 00:10:33.400
Look how beautiful it is.

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:37.200
Here we are driving autonomously into San Francisco.

00:10:38.233 --> 00:10:38.900
You know, this—

00:10:38.900 --> 00:10:39.966
this interchange here—

00:10:39.966 --> 00:10:41.400
always gives me a lot of anxiety,

00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:42.766
because there's so many different highways,

00:10:42.766 --> 00:10:44.833
